---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import "../../styles/global.css";
---

<Layout title="PID Motor Project">
  <section class="p-8 sm:p-12 md:p-16 lg:p-24 max-w-4xl mx-auto">
    <a href="/#projects" class="text-sm text-gray-500 hover:underline">
      ← Back to Home
    </a>

    <h1 class="mt-4 text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-bold text-gray-900">
      PID Motor Controller
    </h1>

    <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2 mt-6">
      <span class="px-3 py-1 bg-gray-900 text-white rounded-lg text-sm">Electrical Design</span>
      <span class="px-3 py-1 bg-gray-900 text-white rounded-lg text-sm">Prototyping</span>
      <span class="px-3 py-1 bg-gray-900 text-white rounded-lg text-sm">Digital logic</span>
      <span class="px-3 py-1 bg-gray-900 text-white rounded-lg text-sm">FETs</span>
      <span class="px-3 py-1 bg-gray-900 text-white rounded-lg text-sm">Latches</span>
      <span class="px-3 py-1 bg-gray-900 text-white rounded-lg text-sm">Counters</span>
    </div>

    <br />

    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
      <img src="/motor1.jpg" class="w-full aspect-square object-cover rounded-md shadow-lg" />
      <img src="/motor3.jpg" class="w-full aspect-square object-cover rounded-md shadow-lg" />
      <img src="/motor2.jpg" class="w-full aspect-square object-cover rounded-md shadow-lg" />
    </div>

   <div class="mt-8 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed space-y-4">
      <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        In this project, a closed-loop servo control system (Fig. 1) was designed, built, tested, and integrated to actively control the rotational speed of a DC motor using analog and digital electronics. 
      </p>
  </div>

  <figure class="mt-8">
    <img
      src="/p1.png"
      alt="Schematic"
      class="w-full h-auto rounded-md shadow-lg"
    />
    <figcaption class="mt-1 text-sm text-gray-500 text-center">
      Fig. 1: Project schematic
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <figure class="mt-8">
    <img
      src="/p2.png"
      alt="Final build"
      class="w-full h-auto rounded-md shadow-lg"
    />
    <figcaption class="mt-1 text-sm text-gray-500 text-center">
      Fig. 2: Final circuit result
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

   <div class="mt-8 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed space-y-4">
      <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        The system measured motor speed using an optical sensor consisting of an LED, a phototransistor, and a slotted rotating disc attached to the motor shaft. 
      </p>
  </div>

   <div class="mt-8 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed space-y-4">
      <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        A timing control circuit was constructed to generate synchronized LATCH and RESET signals from a 5 Hz square-wave input. This ensured that motor speed data could be periodically captured and the counter reset in a controlled manner.
      </p>
  </div>

  <figure class="mt-8">
    <img
      src="/p3.png"
      alt="Schematic"
      class="w-full h-auto rounded-md shadow-lg"
    />
    <figcaption class="mt-1 text-sm text-gray-500 text-center">
      Fig. 3: Latch and reset schematic
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

   <div class="mt-8 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed space-y-4">
      <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        An 8-bit digital counter was built using cascaded divide-by-16 counters to count the number of rotation pulses occurring between reset intervals. The counter output was stored using an 8-bit D-latch, allowing the measured speed to be held stable while processing occurred.
      </p>
  </div>

  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mt-8">
    <figure>
      <img
        src="/p4.png"
        alt="Circuit"
        class="w-full h-auto rounded-md shadow-lg"
      />
      <figcaption class="mt-1 text-sm text-gray-500 text-center">
        Fig. 4: Latch, reset circuit integration with counter
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
  
    <figure>
      <img
        src="/p5.png"
        alt="Output"
        class="w-full h-auto rounded-md shadow-lg"
      />
      <figcaption class="mt-1 text-sm text-gray-500 text-center">
        Fig. 5: Counter logic output
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
  </div>

     <div class="mt-8 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed space-y-4">
        <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
          The latched digital speed value was converted into an analog voltage using an R–2R ladder digital-to-analog converter (DAC). This analog signal represented the measured motor speed and was verified to scale correctly with the digital input.
        </p>
    </div>

  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mt-8">
    <figure>
      <img
        src="/p6.png"
        alt="DAC"
        class="w-full h-auto rounded-md shadow-lg"
      />
      <figcaption class="mt-1 text-sm text-gray-500 text-center">
        Fig. 6: R2R DAC Pinout
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
  
    <figure>
      <img
        src="/p7.png"
        alt="Circuit"
        class="w-full h-auto rounded-md shadow-lg"
      />
      <figcaption class="mt-1 text-sm text-gray-500 text-center">
        Fig. 7: DAC Circuit
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
  </div>

     <div class="mt-8 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed space-y-4">
        <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
          An error signal amplifier was then constructed using operational amplifiers to compare the measured speed voltage to a user-defined setpoint voltage. The resulting error signal was integrated and used to control a power BJT, which regulated the current supplied to the motor, adjusting its speed.
        </p>
    </div>


  <figure class="mt-8">
    <img
      src="/p8.png"
      alt="Circuit"
      class="w-full h-auto rounded-md shadow-lg"
    />
    <figcaption class="mt-1 text-sm text-gray-500 text-center">
      Fig. 8: Error amplifier circuit
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

     <div class="mt-8 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed space-y-4">
        <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
          Finally, all subsystems were integrated into a complete feedback loop. The finished system successfully adjusted motor speed in response to changes in the setpoint, demonstrating stable closed-loop RPM control. The project used feedback, digital counting, DACs, and analog amplification to create a practical motor control application.
        </p>
    </div>


  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mt-8">
    <figure>
      <img
        src="/p9.png"
        alt="Schematic"
        class="w-full h-auto rounded-md shadow-lg"
      />
      <figcaption class="mt-1 text-sm text-gray-500 text-center">
        Fig. 9: Motor control schematic
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
  
    <figure>
      <img
        src="/p10.png"
        alt="Circuit"
        class="w-full h-auto rounded-md shadow-lg"
      />
      <figcaption class="mt-1 text-sm text-gray-500 text-center">
        Fig. 10: Final circuit
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
  </div>

